Introduction

This vignette describes the R package “BERT”. The BERT package was developed to assist CCAMLR’s Working Groups with the estimation of the local biomass of toothfish species in data-poor areas that do not have intergated stock assesments.

The main purpose of this package is to provide functions that: (1) document the most up-to-date CPUE-by-seabed area and Chapman mark-recapture biomass estimation methods agreed by WG-FSA and WG-SAM (2) format the necessary CCAMLR data for input into the biomass estimation method functions

An example has been provided that is similar in lay-out to the R-markdown developed by the Secretariat for WG-FSA-17 (see https://github.com/lucymerobinson/WG-FSA-17) except instead of using “real data” we provide simulated datasets for Research block 486_3 that targets Antartic toothfish (species_code = TOA) and Research block 5843_a1 that targets Patagonian toothfish (species code= TOP). Given data are simulated there are no data extract and processing steps included here, but see paper WG-FSA-17/42 or the R markdown document referred to above for details on these steps.

# load BERT package
library(BERT)

# create four simulated datasets similar to what would be provided in data extracts for Research Blocks 

# catch data - needs unique ID, Season, CRUISE_ID, SET_ID, SPECIES_CODE, CAUGHT_KG_TOTAL, LINE_LENGTH, RESEARCH_BLOCK_CODE

Estimate weight of released tagged fish from observer length-weight data

Fish that are tagged and released are not weighed, but their length is measured. Weights from these released fish are required for both CPUE-by-seabed area and the Chapman mark-recapture based methods Using a logliner model, that is parameterised using length and weight data collected by observers on retained catch, the weights of released fish can be estimated based on thier recorded lengths for both Research Blocks and Reference Areas

Introduction to methods used by CCAMLR to estimate local toothfish biomass

Methods used to estimate local toothfish biomass in the data-poor CCAMLR fisheries include a CPUE-by-seabed-area analogy method (@Agnew2009) and a Chapman tag-recapture estimator (@Hillary2009). Both methods have undergone modification in the working group meetings over the past 10 years with changes to formulas, fixed parameter values, appropriate time series of catch and tagging data for inclusion and the data quality and cleaning processes applied. To address this issue WG-SAM-16 agreed (and documented) a standardised default method of applying the CPUE-by-seabed area and the Chapman tag release-recapture methods of estimating biomass, and requested that the Secretariat apply these methods to provide a single set of biomass estimates of D. mawsoni or D.eleginoides in Research Blocks in Subareas 58.4 and 48.6 that could be further evaluated by WG-FSA (SC-CAMLR-XXXV, Annex 5, paragraph 2.28). Based on these biomass estimates, precautionary catch limits were calculated at WG-FSA-16 by applying a 4% exploitation rate (see Annex 7, Table 1 SC-CCAMLR XXXV). The Scientific Committee noted that there were often large differences between estimates for D. mawsoni using the agreed CPUE-by-seabed area analogy method and the Chapman tag-recapture estimator and that catch limits based on the lower of two estimates would results in catch limits that were substantially lower than those that had been set in previous seasons. Given such a reduction in catch may compromise existing research plans in some areas, catch limits were “rolled-over” from the 2016 season to the 2017 season (para 3.185, SC-CCAMLR XXXV) and it was requested that WG-SAM prioritize the development of approaches to incorporate uncertainty associated with biomass estimates, including through bootstrapped estimates of uncertainty (para 3.187, SC-CCAMLR XXXV).

A bootstrap method of estimating uncertainty in Chapman tag-based biomass estimates was presented at WG-FSA-15 (@Burch2015). The Working Group welcomed the development, but noted that additional analyses were required (SC-CAMLR-XXXIV, Annex 7, para 5.15). WG-SAM-16 requested that the Secretariat work with members to further develop a bootstrapping approach to estimate uncertainty in both the tag-based and CPUE-by-seabed area estimates of biomass (SC-CAMLR-XXXV, Annex 5, para 2.32). The bootstrap method for estimating uncertainty in both methods was documented and applied to estimate an annual time series of biomass in Research Blocks in Subareas 58.4 and 48.6 from fishing seasons 2009-2016 (WG-SAM-17/12). WG-SAM-17 agreed that the comparison of confidence intervals, that were derived using the bootstrap method, around biomass estimates in the same Research Blocks using different methods were a useful indicator of whether methods were appropriate. It further noted that generally confidence intervals were overlapping between the two estimates where Patagonian toothfish were targeted, but they did not generally overlap where Antarctic toothfish were the dominant species (WG-SAM-17, para 3.2). It was also noted that where confidence intervals did not overlap indicated that there were issues with the underlying data, parameter values and/or methodological assumptions (WG-SAM-17, para 3.3).

To explain why estimates using the two different methods were not overlapping, WG-SAM-17 recalled that the advice from WG-SAM-16 had been to use the current spawning stock biomass as the reference area biomass in the CPUE-by-seabed area calculation, but that the current vulnerable biomass should be used in this calculation because the gear used in toothfish fisheries typically selects immature and mature fish (WG-SAM-17, para 3.10). WG-SAM-17 also noted that the seabed area used for the Ross Sea Region in the CPUE-by-seabed area calculation used the entire fishable area, but the Working Group agreed that the CPUE-by-seabed area calculation should only use seabed area from SSRUs that were open to fishing (WG-SAM-17, para 3.10). Given the suggested changes to the reference area biomass and the seabed area parameter values in the Ross Sea reference area it was anticipated that revised estimates would be higher than those presented previously (especially for Antarctic toothfish). Hence the Working Group requested that the Secretariat provide revised estimates using the CPUE-by-seabed area method to WG-FSA-17 based on the revised parameter values (para 3.11, WG-SAM-17).

In response to this request the Secretariat provided biomass estimates of toothfish populations with bootstrapped confidence intervals in Research Blocks in Subareas 48.2, 48.6, 58.4 and 88.3 for evaluation by WG-FSA-17 and the BERT R package facilitates the repeatability and transparency of those results.

CPUE-by-seabed area

The point estimation of local biomass using the catch-per-unit-effort (CPUE) by seabed area analogy was agreed at WG-SAM-16; 2.28 and defined as

\[ B_x = \frac{I_x \times A_x \times B_r}{I_r \times Ar} \] Eqn 1

Where the subscripts \(x\) and \(r\) denote the parameter from the research block and reference area respectively. Different reference areas were selected for Research Blocks depending on the target species. WG-SAM-16 agreed that the Ross Sea Region should be used as a reference area for Research Blocks that target D.mawsoni and the HIMI area should be used as a reference area for Research Blocks that target D.eleginoides (WG-SAM-16, para 2.30).

\(Ix\) is the median of the haul by haul CPUE (kg/km) over the past three seasons in which fishing has occurred in Research Block \(x\). For example, if fishing has occurred in 2017, 2015 and 2014 then all of these hauls will be included in calculating the median CPUE for the 2017 fishing season.

\(Ir\) is the median of the haul by haul CPUE (kg/km) over the past three seasons that relates to the season of the assessment that was used to generate the reference area Biomass \(r\). For example if the 2017 assessment was used to generate the reference area biomass then hauls from the 2017,2016 and 2015 seasons would be included

In both \(Ix\) and \(Ir\) The total fish weight included in the CPUE included the total catch (kg) on a haul, including fish that were tagged and released (where the weight of released fish is estimated using the length–weight relationship for that area) is divided by the length of line (km) reported for that set in the C2 data (WG-SAM-16, paragraph 2.36).

\(Ax\) is the seabed area (km2) in Research Block x in the depth range 600–1800 m using a processed version of the GEBCO 2014 dataset (See Figure 1 and CCAMLR Secretariat, 2015).\(Ar\) is the seabed area (km2) in the same depth range (i.e. 600-1800m) in the reference area \(r\). Consistent with advice from WG-SAM-17, the seabed area included in the Ross Sea reference area (i.e. RSR_open) only included Small Scale Research Units (SSRUs) that are open to fishing (para 3.11, WG-SAM-17). In the HIMI referemce area \(Ar\)=117067.75 km2 and in the RSR_open reference area \(Ar\)=120928.75 km2 (see Figure 1). \(Br\) was the current vulnerable biomass (para 3.10 WG-SAM-17) from the 2017 integrated assessments in the Ross Sea, which was estimated to be 92693.07 t of Antarctic toothfish, and the HIMI assessment, which was estimated to be 43993.03 t of Patagonian toothfish. Variation in the reference areas biomass estimates was included with CV values of 0.073 from the Ross Sea Assessment and 0.072 from the HIMI Assessment. Mean and CV values were provided by New Zealand Scientists for the Ross Sea Assessment and Australian Scientists for the HIMI assessment.

The uncertainty around the point estimates was calculated using a non-parameteric bootstrap (Efron and Tibshirani 1993; Chernick 2008). The following steps were applied

  1. The hauls for the research block and the reference area are sampled with replacement.Noting that all zero catch hauls were included in bootstrap resampling.
  2. Median values,\(I^i_x\) and \(I^i_r\), calculated for each the ith bootstrap replicates.
  3. The uncertainty in the reference area biomass was quantified by generating a log normally distributed random number with mean \(B_r\) and a standard deviation that is the square root of the coefficient of variation of \(B_r\). For each ith bootstrap replicate we calculate biomass, as

\[ B^i_x = \frac{I^i_x \times A_x \times B^i_r}{I^i_r \times A_r}. \] Eqn 2

The areas of the research block and the reference area (\(A_x\),\(A_r\)) were assumed to be known without error and are therefore not contributed to the uncertainty in the bootstrap.

The uncertainty was then quantified by taking quantiles of the \(B^i_x\), for example, 95% confidence intervals are the 0.025 and 0.975 quantiles.

Both point estimates and estimates of uncertainty using the CPUE-by-seabed area method were generated using the BERT R package (Burch and Robinson, 2017).

Chapman mark-recapture estimator

The point estimation of local biomass using the Chapman mark-recapture-based method was agreed at WG-SAM-16; 2.28 and defined as:

\[B_j = \frac{c_j(n_{j-1}+1)}{mx_j+1}\] Eqn 3

where \(n_{j–1}\) is the number of tagged fish available for recapture at the end of the season prior to season \(j\), \(c_j\) is the catch in season \(j\) (as with CPUE the catch includes fish that are tagged and released, as these fish are scanned for tags upon capture) and \(mx_j\) is the number of tagged fish recaptured in season \(j\) (excluding within-season recaptures).

The agreed calculation for the number of tagged fish available for recapture is:

\[ N_j = \begin{cases} j=1, r_j(1-t)e^{-(f+M)}-m_j \\ j>1, n_{j-1} \end{cases} \]
Eqn 4

\(r_j\) is the total number of fish released in CCAMLR fishing season \(j\), \(m_j\) is the total number of tagged fish recaptured in CCAMLR fishing season \(j\) and \(n_{j–1}\) is the number of tagged fish available for recapture at the end of the season prior to season \(j\), \(t\) is the post-tagging mortality rate of 0.1 (Agnew 2006), \(f\) is the annual tag loss rate which is 0.0084 (WG-SAM-11/18) \(M\) is natural mortality where \(M\) = 0.13 for Antarctic toothfish (D. mawsoni) (WG-FSA-SAM-06/08) and 0.155 for Patagonian toothfish (D. eleginoides) (Candy 2011).

In the absence of an estimate of movement, the number of tagged fish available for recapture was calculated using a three-year moving window that was applied to release data to account for potential movement-related bias (SC-CAMLR-XXXV/05, paragraph 2.34). For example an estimate of the population size in 2015 would be based on the available tagged fish that were released in 2012, 2013 and 2014, while an estimate of the population size in 2016 would be based on the available tagged fish that were released in 2013, 2014 and 2015.

The uncertainty around the point estimates was calculated using a non-parametric bootstrap (Efron and Tibshirani 1993; Chernick 2008). This uncertainty in the estimate is made up of two components. Firstly the expected number tagged fish that are available for recapture immediately prior to fishing is given by Eqn 4 for the assumed values of tag-induced mortality, tag-loss and natural mortality. In the estimation of uncertainty, the probability that a tagged fish will survive tagging, natural mortality and not lose its tags is assumed independent from other tagged fish. We undertook the following steps, implementing the probability of each tagged fish surviving the tagging process and the annual natural morality and tag loss as Bernoulli trials (Binomial probabilities).

  1. Tag release mortality is applied in the season of release
  2. The recaptures are removed and scaled by the tag-reporting rate, noting that tag-reporting rate is currently assumed to be 100%.
  3. Natural mortality and tag loss are implemented

Steps 2 and 3 were then repeated for each season that the tags are at liberty, but tag release mortality is only applied in the first season. For the ith bootstrap replicate this represents the \(n^i_{j–1}\). All processes (e.g. tag-induced mortality, natural mortality, tag-loss) were implemented as instantaneous rates to account for processes such as natural mortality and tag-loss that compete with one another to decrease the number of available tags over the season.

Secondly, we need to account for the uncertainty in the haul data. If the experiment was repeated we would not expect to recapture the same number of tagged fish. To account for this uncertainty in the bootstrap the following process is applied

  1. The hauls in the season were sampled with replacement.Noting that zero tagged-fish recapture and zero catch hauls were included in bootstrapped resampling.
  2. The sum of the catches and the recaptures in the ith bootstrap replicate were calculated as the \(c^i_j\) and \(mx^i_j\) respectively.

Bootstrap replicates of the haul data where there were zero tag recaptures were used to estimate biomass (\(B^i_j\)). If the Petersen method had been used the would have been infinite.

For each bootstrap iteration was calculated as:

\[B^i_j = \frac{c^i_j(n^i_{j-1}+1)}{mx^i_j+1}\]

The uncertainty was then quantified by taking quantiles of the \(B^i_x\), for example, 95% confidence intervals are the 0.025 and 0.975 quantiles.

Both point estimates and estimates of uncertainty using the Chapman method were generated using the tagr package (Burch and Robinson, 2017).

Note that in the results the TOA abbreviation for D.mawsoni (TOA) and D.eleginoides (TOP) are used consistently throughout the results below.

Results

Ancillary information on the data that were used in calculating those estimates (i.e. numbers of recaptures and numbers of hauls) were also provided to give some indication of the amount of data that was used in calculating the corresponding estimates.
